89
00:03:12,022 --> 00:03:14,724
about the people involved in creating a cinematic.

90
00:03:14,724 --> 00:03:16,165
At the top of our hierarchy, of course,

91
00:03:16,165 --> 00:03:17,807
we've got our creative director,

92
00:03:17,807 --> 00:03:20,009
who provided the overarching vision of the story

93
00:03:20,009 --> 00:03:21,590
and oversaw the broad strokes

94
00:03:21,590 --> 00:03:24,072
of the cinematic production process.

95
00:03:24,072 --> 00:03:27,215
We had our writers, Matt Sophos and Rich Galbert,

96
00:03:27,215 --> 00:03:28,736
who would present the director's vision

97
00:03:28,736 --> 00:03:29,537
in the form of scripts.

98
00:03:30,652 --> 00:03:33,014
Our director of photography, Doria Razzi,

99
00:03:33,014 --> 00:03:36,096
who designed the detailed plan for executing that vision

100
00:03:36,096 --> 00:03:39,119
scene by scene with a consistent cinematic language.

101
00:03:39,119 --> 00:03:41,381
And there's the rest of our team,

102
00:03:41,381 --> 00:03:43,002
such as our animation director, Bruno,

103
00:03:43,002 --> 00:03:45,885
who provided the context for our character acting choices

104
00:03:45,885 --> 00:03:47,926
and would give feedback on the animation quality.

105
00:03:48,846 --> 00:03:50,106
myself, the animation lead,

106
00:03:50,106 --> 00:03:52,848
responsible for the day-to-day production process

107
00:03:52,848 --> 00:03:54,828
and ensuring the animators had everything they needed

108
00:03:54,828 --> 00:03:56,429
to work to the best of their abilities,

109
00:03:56,429 --> 00:03:58,490
also providing feedback.

110
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:00,130
All of our animators, several of which

111
00:04:00,130 --> 00:04:01,371
aren't in this photo, sadly,

112
00:04:01,371 --> 00:04:03,392
but they were expected to maintain

113
00:04:03,392 --> 00:04:05,092
a certain level of self-autonomy

114
00:04:05,092 --> 00:04:06,893
with ownership of their assigned scenes

115
00:04:06,893 --> 00:04:07,853
from start to finish.

116
00:04:07,853 --> 00:04:10,634
They would work very closely with our cinematic artist,

117
00:04:10,634 --> 00:04:11,735
who would wrangle the cameras,

118
00:04:11,735 --> 00:04:13,475
and they would send all of that data

119
00:04:13,475 --> 00:04:14,736
over to our integration team

120
00:04:14,736 --> 00:04:16,337
to put the scenes into the game engine.

121
00:04:16,964 --> 00:04:18,905
And of course, we can't forget our support staff,

122
00:04:18,905 --> 00:04:22,107
such as our producers and our outsource coordinator

123
00:04:22,107 --> 00:04:24,868
who made sure everything was running smoothly

124
00:04:24,868 --> 00:04:25,688
and getting done on time.

125
00:04:25,688 --> 00:04:28,090
I'd like to break down our production

126
00:04:28,090 --> 00:04:31,451
into three main phases where we were able

127
00:04:31,451 --> 00:04:35,513
to streamline our workflow for no-cut cinematics.

128
00:04:35,513 --> 00:04:38,535
Pre-visualization, or pre-vis for short,

129
00:04:38,535 --> 00:04:40,616
everything we did on set at the mocap stage,

130
00:04:40,616 --> 00:04:43,718
and scene assembly and polish of all of that data.

131
00:04:46,471 --> 00:04:47,891
So let's start with pre-visualization.

132
00:04:47,891 --> 00:04:50,132
And if you see the picture in the background,

133
00:04:50,132 --> 00:04:52,813
you might get a little hint of where we went there.

134
00:04:52,813 --> 00:04:53,974
Let's start with a little history.

135
00:04:53,974 --> 00:04:56,675
On previous God of War projects,

136
00:04:56,675 --> 00:04:59,456
all of our layout was done in Maya.

137
00:04:59,456 --> 00:05:01,697
This is all right, our camera language was pretty simple.

138
00:05:01,697 --> 00:05:03,117
We really only had one main rule,

139
00:05:03,117 --> 00:05:04,638
which was to keep the camera alive.

140
00:05:04,638 --> 00:05:06,238
So we didn't have any static shots.

141
00:05:06,238 --> 00:05:09,620
You can see it might move to follow Kratos' gaze.

142
00:05:09,620 --> 00:05:11,940
It might push in a little bit to focus on his daughter

143
00:05:11,940 --> 00:05:13,041
as we come into the scene.

144
00:05:14,058 --> 00:05:16,901
we would use cuts to show details and character reactions.

145
00:05:16,901 --> 00:05:18,984
But there wasn't much attention paid

146
00:05:18,984 --> 00:05:20,225
to lens choice or anything.

147
00:05:20,225 --> 00:05:22,187
This was pretty passable,

148
00:05:22,187 --> 00:05:26,391
but we realized this method did not work with no cuts.

149
00:05:26,391 --> 00:05:29,695
Here's a very early test scene from this current project,

150
00:05:29,695 --> 00:05:31,156
and I'm gonna kinda rip it apart

151
00:05:31,156 --> 00:05:33,198
and talk about the failure points.

152
00:05:33,198 --> 00:05:34,480
This is my scene, so I can do that.

153
00:05:36,504 --> 00:05:38,785
So, you could see, first of all,

154
00:05:38,785 --> 00:05:41,786
the characters tended to freeze in place.

155
00:05:41,786 --> 00:05:43,807
We didn't really know what to do with them,

156
00:05:43,807 --> 00:05:45,867
and that forced the camera to swing around

157
00:05:45,867 --> 00:05:47,668
and traverse great distances

158
00:05:47,668 --> 00:05:49,369
without really any motivation to do so.

159
00:05:49,369 --> 00:05:52,290
I was trying to get reaction shots on their faces

160
00:05:52,290 --> 00:05:53,310
as they talked to each other,

161
00:05:53,310 --> 00:05:54,910
but again, since I froze them in place,

162
00:05:54,910 --> 00:05:57,111
I didn't really know what to do with the camera,

163
00:05:57,111 --> 00:05:59,052
so it would move around kind of awkwardly.

164
00:05:59,052 --> 00:05:59,952
It wasn't really grounded

165
00:05:59,952 --> 00:06:01,793
the way a real camera person would behave.

166
00:06:02,405 --> 00:06:03,666
If you look at the start of a scene,

167
00:06:03,666 --> 00:06:05,648
you could see that the camera is just way too high.

168
00:06:05,648 --> 00:06:07,109
A person would have to be floating in the air

169
00:06:07,109 --> 00:06:08,170
in order to get that shot.

170
00:06:08,170 --> 00:06:10,352
And then it very quickly swings around

171
00:06:10,352 --> 00:06:13,335
and starts going backwards across an entire field.

172
00:06:13,335 --> 00:06:16,878
And it was also just a very time-consuming process

173
00:06:16,878 --> 00:06:19,841
for something that didn't yield very great results.

174
00:06:19,841 --> 00:06:21,422
What we really needed was someone

175
00:06:21,422 --> 00:06:22,923
with experience in staging,

176
00:06:22,923 --> 00:06:24,184
who could help us tackle oners

177
00:06:24,184 --> 00:06:25,866
in a more sophisticated way.

178
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:28,321
So that's when we hired Doria Rossi.

179
00:06:28,321 --> 00:06:31,322
And with Doria on board, we began to think about

180
00:06:31,322 --> 00:06:33,643
staging our scenes as a complex dance

181
00:06:33,643 --> 00:06:34,863
between actors and the camera.

182
00:06:34,863 --> 00:06:37,384
We would often use top-down diagrams to plan the scenes.

183
00:06:37,384 --> 00:06:40,145
Most of the time this was just done on a whiteboard

184
00:06:40,145 --> 00:06:42,345
with some markers, but here I've cleaned it up

185
