239
00:09:04,170 --> 00:09:05,772
and get a sense of timing.

240
00:09:05,772 --> 00:09:08,054
Most often we just set a camera down somewhere

241
00:09:08,054 --> 00:09:09,095
and shoot ourselves.

242
00:09:09,095 --> 00:09:11,997
This was Sophie Evans getting some cool Kratos motion.

243
00:09:11,997 --> 00:09:14,519
And this works great for our gameplay animators.

244
00:09:14,519 --> 00:09:16,841
They use it to, you know, figure out new moves.

245
00:09:16,841 --> 00:09:18,843
And the cinematics team was wondering,

246
00:09:18,843 --> 00:09:20,824
well how could we leverage that for our cinematics?

247
00:09:20,824 --> 00:09:23,366
Could we take the camera off the tripod

248
00:09:23,366 --> 00:09:25,948
and start shooting scenes with it?

249
00:09:25,948 --> 00:09:26,469
Yes you can.

250
00:09:27,650 --> 00:09:30,511
Some of the benefits of this were we could easily test

251
00:09:30,511 --> 00:09:31,632
different styles of camera,

252
00:09:31,632 --> 00:09:33,612
and Dory wanted to try a documentary style,

253
00:09:33,612 --> 00:09:36,234
you know, more grounded and using handheld.

254
00:09:36,234 --> 00:09:38,355
It took very little setup time.

255
00:09:38,355 --> 00:09:40,916
You could just grab an SLR, grab a couple animators,

256
00:09:40,916 --> 00:09:43,297
go outside and shoot.

257
00:09:43,297 --> 00:09:44,398
It was very quick to review.

258
00:09:44,398 --> 00:09:46,118
We could shoot in a couple hours,

259
00:09:46,118 --> 00:09:47,359
do a review with Corey,

260
00:09:47,359 --> 00:09:48,860
and do reshoots within the same day.

261
00:09:50,836 --> 00:09:52,918
you would get a lot of surprising human interactions

262
00:09:52,918 --> 00:09:54,901
just riffing off each other from take to take

263
00:09:54,901 --> 00:09:55,902
that you might not think about

264
00:09:55,902 --> 00:09:59,527
when you were sitting at a computer doing layout in Maya.

265
00:09:59,527 --> 00:10:00,127
Plus, it's just a lot of fun.

266
00:10:00,127 --> 00:10:02,530
You know, you get out of your chair,

267
00:10:02,530 --> 00:10:05,614
you get a little exercise, you look a little ridiculous,

268
00:10:05,614 --> 00:10:07,356
you confuse all your neighbors around you,

269
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:08,137
and it's pretty awesome.

270
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:11,681
Some of the challenges, of course,

271
00:10:11,681 --> 00:10:14,004
are memorizing lots of lines.

