361
00:14:19,712 --> 00:14:21,833
We had the luxury of having our own Vicon space

362
00:14:21,833 --> 00:14:24,275
within our studio, but with Oners,

363
00:14:24,275 --> 00:14:25,816
this actually became a necessity.

364
00:14:26,552 --> 00:14:30,335
So some of the benefits of that was that we could actually

365
00:14:30,335 --> 00:14:31,777
work with characters of varying sizes

366
00:14:31,777 --> 00:14:35,239
without having to shuffle around on our knees.

367
00:14:35,239 --> 00:14:36,580
We could see our actual sets and props to scale.

368
00:14:36,580 --> 00:14:39,743
We could get more accurate plans for our principal shoot days

369
00:14:39,743 --> 00:14:41,865
we could figure out how many different mocap volumes

370
00:14:41,865 --> 00:14:43,606
we would need and figure out how we would divide up

371
00:14:43,606 --> 00:14:45,448
our environments to accomplish that.

372
00:14:45,448 --> 00:14:49,331
All of that data could then be sent over to the stage

373
00:14:49,331 --> 00:14:50,072
to prep for our shoot.

374
00:14:50,072 --> 00:14:53,394
And anything that we shoot could also be exported

375
00:14:53,394 --> 00:14:55,196
as a prototype to be put in the game engine.

376
00:14:56,958 --> 00:14:59,259
Some of the challenges of working with motion capture,

377
00:14:59,259 --> 00:15:03,282
of course, are learning to operate a mocap system.

378
00:15:03,282 --> 00:15:05,464
Blade is not the most user-friendly piece of software,

379
00:15:05,464 --> 00:15:06,805
and we would often have camera issues

380
00:15:06,805 --> 00:15:08,666
getting all the cameras calibrated.

381
00:15:08,666 --> 00:15:11,268
Our virtual camera's monitor often shorted out

382
00:15:11,268 --> 00:15:14,150
due to cabling issues, so we had some hardware difficulties.

383
00:15:14,150 --> 00:15:16,712
MotionBuilder was unstable with our plugins sometimes,

384
00:15:16,712 --> 00:15:20,334
and tended to crash when we worked with a very large scene.

385
00:15:20,334 --> 00:15:21,155
So stuff like that.

386
00:15:22,193 --> 00:15:23,955
It was also a much slower iteration time

387
00:15:23,955 --> 00:15:27,117
than live action previs because you had to set up the volume,

388
00:15:27,117 --> 00:15:28,579
you had to get the animator suited up,

389
00:15:28,579 --> 00:15:31,421
we had to shoot the thing, we had to tear it down,

390
00:15:31,421 --> 00:15:33,763
then we had to assemble the scene,

391
00:15:33,763 --> 00:15:34,704
then we had to render it.

392
00:15:34,704 --> 00:15:37,166
So it was a little more difficult to iterate quickly,

393
00:15:37,166 --> 00:15:39,988
at least a one day turnaround just to shoot it.

394
00:15:39,988 --> 00:15:41,950
It tended to divert our animators away

395
00:15:41,950 --> 00:15:43,711
because they were getting in the suit and shooting,

396
00:15:43,711 --> 00:15:44,672
and it was a lot of fun,

397
00:15:44,672 --> 00:15:46,053
but then they were spending time shooting

398
00:15:46,053 --> 00:15:47,654
instead of animating.

399
00:15:47,654 --> 00:15:49,176
When production ramped up significantly,

400
00:15:49,176 --> 00:15:51,898
we would hire temp actors to fill in those roles.

401
00:15:52,332 --> 00:15:57,014
But the concern was always that because the animator was not in the suit and in the moment

402
00:15:57,014 --> 00:16:01,996
with the pre-vis process, they might have less creative input in their ownership of

403
00:16:01,996 --> 00:16:03,877
their scenes, so we were always concerned about that.

404
00:16:03,877 --> 00:16:09,899
We're thinking of maybe ways to involve the main owner of the scene, but then hire temp

405
00:16:09,899 --> 00:16:11,740
actors to fill in the rest of the characters for the scene.

