00:22:04,172 --> 00:22:06,314
almost a different scene entirely.

531
00:22:06,314 --> 00:22:08,516
So we had this whole moment where these icicles

532
00:22:08,516 --> 00:22:10,478
were gonna break down and break off

533
00:22:10,478 --> 00:22:11,259
the front part of the ship.

534
00:22:11,259 --> 00:22:14,141
But then the rest of it is pretty similar

535
00:22:14,141 --> 00:22:17,004
to what we ended up shooting and animating

536
00:22:17,004 --> 00:22:17,945
for the final product.

537
00:22:17,945 --> 00:22:21,669
We've got the barrels rolling down, or whatever that is.

538
00:22:25,115 --> 00:22:26,576
and then they crash.

539
00:22:26,576 --> 00:22:27,817
And an interesting thing to note here

540
00:22:27,817 --> 00:22:30,639
in the original previz is that Kratos jumps first,

541
00:22:30,639 --> 00:22:33,641
so it was a cool change to have Atreus lead the way

542
00:22:33,641 --> 00:22:35,523
in the final version.

543
00:22:35,523 --> 00:22:40,627
All right, so once you've got your previz all done,

544
00:22:40,627 --> 00:22:46,251
you've got it approved, it is time to go on set.

545
00:22:46,251 --> 00:22:47,152
All right.

546
00:22:47,152 --> 00:22:50,574
On previous projects, we would sometimes

547
00:22:50,574 --> 00:22:52,316
do our set construction, our rehearsal,

548
00:22:52,316 --> 00:22:54,317
even our shoots, all on the same day.

549
00:22:55,432 --> 00:22:58,953
We didn't have a virtual camera because we were doing all the camera work in Maya.

550
00:22:58,953 --> 00:23:03,396
So there was a little bit of room for choreography experiments, letting the actors run around

551
00:23:03,396 --> 00:23:05,977
and see what they could, you know, come up with.

552
00:23:05,977 --> 00:23:09,939
But again, no cuts means it's not really great to try improv.

553
00:23:09,939 --> 00:23:14,322
This scene was really the only time we were on stage and didn't have Previs ready, so

554
00:23:14,322 --> 00:23:15,322
we just kind of winged it.

555
00:23:16,246 --> 00:23:18,607
And you can start to see some of the same failure points

556
00:23:18,607 --> 00:23:19,847
you encountered in our early tests.

557
00:23:19,847 --> 00:23:20,788
What is it, boy?

558
00:23:20,788 --> 00:23:22,508
Some very unmotivated camera motions

559
00:23:22,508 --> 00:23:25,349
because the actors had frozen and Dory needed

560
00:23:25,349 --> 00:23:27,230
to go and see their faces.

561
00:23:27,230 --> 00:23:29,791
So we just kind of swung around to try to get their reactions.

562
00:23:29,791 --> 00:23:33,333
And then we had to swing back around because we had

563
00:23:33,333 --> 00:23:34,973
to get back to game camera.

564
00:23:34,973 --> 00:23:36,814
So there wasn't really any motivation for that move

565
00:23:36,814 --> 00:23:39,235
either, but we wanted to see Atreus' face

566
00:23:39,235 --> 00:23:40,475
and we needed to get back to the game.

567
00:23:43,938 --> 00:23:46,460
In the end, this data, I don't know,

568
00:23:46,460 --> 00:23:49,363
we just didn't like it, so we ended up throwing it out,

569
00:23:49,363 --> 00:23:50,664
and we did a proper previs pass,

570
00:23:50,664 --> 00:23:52,005
and we came back to the stage later.

571
00:23:52,005 --> 00:23:54,087
It also helped to have more context

572
00:23:54,087 --> 00:23:56,149
for where the scene was taking place,

573
00:23:56,149 --> 00:23:58,210
and it was taking place in a boat.

574
00:23:58,210 --> 00:23:59,311
Again, I said nothing.

575
00:23:59,311 --> 00:24:01,553
All right, let's shoot some previs for the boat.

576
00:24:03,648 --> 00:24:04,208
What is it, boy?

577
00:24:04,208 --> 00:24:05,869
You can see here we were able to figure out

578
00:24:05,869 --> 00:24:08,350
how to get the actors to face the camera.

579
00:24:08,350 --> 00:24:09,671
You don't hear that?

580
00:24:09,671 --> 00:24:11,132
Dory was able to do some more thinking

581
00:24:11,132 --> 00:24:14,154
about how he wanted to do the lensing.

582
00:24:14,154 --> 00:24:15,735
What's going on right now?

583
00:24:15,735 --> 00:24:17,335
And we would do a zoom in

584
00:24:17,335 --> 00:24:21,838
and get a really nice intimate shot here.

585
00:24:21,838 --> 00:24:22,979
Lots of voices, angry.

586
00:24:22,979 --> 00:24:23,879
You really didn't hear that?

587
00:24:23,879 --> 00:24:24,079
No.

588
00:24:24,079 --> 00:24:28,222
We had this nice moment with them.

589
00:24:28,222 --> 00:24:29,282
It felt

590
00:24:31,974 --> 00:24:37,402
And then we could use the motion of Atreus turning to sit back down on the boat as motivation

591
00:24:37,402 --> 00:24:38,984
for the camera to move and get back into the camera.

592
00:24:38,984 --> 00:24:44,292
So again, every scene had to be meticulously planned.

593
00:24:44,292 --> 00:24:47,757
So no more winging it on the set, have pre-vis every single time.

594
00:24:49,750 --> 00:24:52,613
Another big aspect of not winging it was breaking up

595
00:24:52,613 --> 00:24:55,855
our mo-cap shoots and having a specific tech day.

596
00:24:55,855 --> 00:24:58,477
So no actors on set, just the animators and Dory

597
00:24:58,477 --> 00:25:00,619
and everybody who needed to be there to review

598
00:25:00,619 --> 00:25:03,561
our exported data and our videos from the previous process

599
00:25:03,561 --> 00:25:07,064
with the stage crew, discussing and reviewing any props

600
00:25:07,064 --> 00:25:08,085
we would need for the shoot day,

601
00:25:08,085 --> 00:25:11,107
dividing up our volume space,

602
00:25:11,107 --> 00:25:13,048
figuring out which sets we wanted to construct.

603
00:25:14,515 --> 00:25:16,839
laying down tape for all our major choreography beats,

604
00:25:16,839 --> 00:25:19,103
and this was useful when we had our mo-cap previews,

605
00:25:19,103 --> 00:25:20,766
we could actually measure that in MotionBuilder

606
00:25:20,766 --> 00:25:21,547
and get that all down.

607
00:25:21,547 --> 00:25:24,772
And finally, just go over our shot list,

608
00:25:24,772 --> 00:25:26,155
finalize any last minute details

609
00:25:26,155 --> 00:25:27,217
so that when the actors showed up,

610
00:25:27,217 --> 00:25:29,060
they were ready to go and we could just start rehearsing.

611
00:25:31,272 --> 00:25:33,434
Now getting those assets to the stage for Tech Day

612
00:25:33,434 --> 00:25:34,835
posed a little bit of a challenge,

613
00:25:34,835 --> 00:25:37,698
and that's where we had our tech artists give us an assist.

614
00:25:37,698 --> 00:25:39,540
They wrote a tool for us which we called

615
00:25:39,540 --> 00:25:40,901
the Maya to Motion Builder tool,

616
00:25:40,901 --> 00:25:43,043
and that allowed our animators to export

617
00:25:43,043 --> 00:25:46,125
our proprietary animation rigs into Motion Builder

618
00:25:46,125 --> 00:25:47,707
at the correct scale and orientation,

619
00:25:47,707 --> 00:25:49,628
and we didn't need to bake anims or anything,

620
00:25:49,628 --> 00:25:51,110
so that saved us a lot of time.

621
00:25:51,110 --> 00:25:53,672
One of the big pain points, however,

622
00:25:53,672 --> 00:25:55,754
was exporting our environments into Motion Builder.

623
00:25:56,913 --> 00:25:59,555
See, on our project, we use a proprietary thing

624
00:25:59,555 --> 00:26:02,457
called ref nodes, which are similar to like Unity prefabs,

625
00:26:02,457 --> 00:26:05,079
and those need to be converted to regular geometry

626
00:26:05,079 --> 00:26:06,880
in order to be compatible with MotionBuilder.

627
00:26:06,880 --> 00:26:08,782
And this was a very slow process.

628
00:26:08,782 --> 00:26:11,664
I mean, there's just hundreds or thousands of assets

629
00:26:11,664 --> 00:26:13,926
in just this one piece alone, the house.

630
00:26:13,926 --> 00:26:17,148
That converted geo then needed to be parented under a node

631
00:26:17,148 --> 00:26:19,410
so that it could be moved from world space

632
00:26:19,410 --> 00:26:21,852
to the mocap space, which is like that green space there

633
00:26:21,852 --> 00:26:24,474
at the origin, and then back again after the shoot.

634
00:26:25,235 --> 00:26:26,356
And this was all done by hand,

635
00:26:26,356 --> 00:26:27,997
so there was lots of room for human error,

636
00:26:27,997 --> 00:26:30,379
especially when onboarding new team members.

637
00:26:30,379 --> 00:26:32,160
So we're now developing an automation tool

638
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:33,942
similar to Maya to MotionBuilder,

639
00:26:33,942 --> 00:26:35,843
but for converting environment geometry.

640
00:26:35,843 --> 00:26:40,026
Once we're on the set, there were quite a few people there.

641
00:26:40,026 --> 00:26:43,969
We had our creative director, of course, our writers.

642
00:26:45,195 --> 00:26:46,616
Our director of photography was there,

643
00:26:46,616 --> 00:26:47,797
the animation director was there,

644
00:26:47,797 --> 00:26:49,818
the animation lead was there, our producers were there,

645
00:26:49,818 --> 00:26:53,481
our dialogue coordinator, the stage crew, and animators.

646
00:26:53,481 --> 00:26:55,622
Whoo, lots of cooks in the kitchen.

647
00:26:55,622 --> 00:26:58,724
So it was very important to define roles on the set

648
00:26:58,724 --> 00:27:00,225
so the actors weren't getting overwhelmed

649
00:27:00,225 --> 00:27:01,766
by feedback coming from too many directions.

650
00:27:01,766 --> 00:27:04,928
What we ended up doing was having our creative director

651
00:27:04,928 --> 00:27:08,310
or writers focus with the actors on their performance notes.

652
00:27:08,310 --> 00:27:11,873
Our director of photography would focus on staging notes.

653
00:27:12,766 --> 00:27:14,108
and our animation director would focus

654
00:27:14,108 --> 00:27:16,250
on any kind of body mechanics notes.

655
00:27:16,250 --> 00:27:17,812
So if anybody else had feedback to give

656
00:27:17,812 --> 00:27:20,776
for any of these things, they could go to our point people

657
00:27:20,776 --> 00:27:22,178
and give them the feedback,

658
00:27:22,178 --> 00:27:23,800
and then they could relay it to the actors,

659
00:27:23,800 --> 00:27:25,802
so the actors knew who to go to when they needed feedback.

660
00:27:27,937 --> 00:27:30,439
And what would the animators do on set?

661
00:27:30,439 --> 00:27:32,180
Ooh, we could use them as stage hands.

662
00:27:32,180 --> 00:27:33,701
Again, they were owning their scene,

663
00:27:33,701 --> 00:27:36,003
so they know it and they know all the elements within it,

664
00:27:36,003 --> 00:27:38,385
so they really were helpful in being able

665
00:27:38,385 --> 00:27:40,887
to present the previous videos and talk through it.

666
00:27:40,887 --> 00:27:43,549
They could inform other people about any entrances,

667
00:27:43,549 --> 00:27:46,171
exits, key poses, props that were needed.

668
00:27:46,171 --> 00:27:48,053
They could assist with any stand-in work,

669
00:27:48,053 --> 00:27:49,334
any kind of extra bodies needed

670
00:27:49,334 --> 00:27:51,316
that we didn't have anybody suited up for.

671
00:27:51,316 --> 00:27:53,818
And of course, they were taking notes

672
00:27:53,818 --> 00:27:55,159
on any info coming out of the shoot

673
00:27:55,159 --> 00:27:56,360
so that when they got the data back,

674
00:27:56,360 --> 00:27:57,581
they were ready to hit the ground running.

675
00:27:58,551 --> 00:28:01,313
Here's a few examples of animators as stagehands here.

676
00:28:01,313 --> 00:28:03,455
I'm playing a dead body.

677
00:28:03,455 --> 00:28:03,655
Yep.

678
00:28:03,655 --> 00:28:07,619
And you can see our creative director,

679
00:28:07,619 --> 00:28:10,141
writers, and our dialogue coordinator in the back,

680
00:28:10,141 --> 00:28:14,224
making sure everything's running smoothly.

681
00:28:14,224 --> 00:28:17,927
This is a scene that actually got cut from the game,

682
00:28:17,927 --> 00:28:20,410
but I had a lot of fun playing this creature in the water,

683
00:28:20,410 --> 00:28:22,191
and then our stage crew did an awesome job

684
00:28:22,191 --> 00:28:24,973
building this boat for us that could move around

685
00:28:24,973 --> 00:28:26,335
and act like it was on the water.

686
00:28:28,533 --> 00:28:29,714
Sit down.

687
00:28:29,714 --> 00:28:34,035
This is not a game.

688
00:28:34,035 --> 00:28:35,136
Here you can see our boat rig

689
00:28:35,136 --> 00:28:37,816
being used for a more intense scene.

690
00:28:37,816 --> 00:28:39,597
This is the introduction of Jormungandr,

691
00:28:39,597 --> 00:28:42,318
the giant world serpent coming out of the water.

692
00:28:42,318 --> 00:28:45,379
And I'd like to take this moment to talk a little bit

693
00:28:45,379 --> 00:28:48,340
about multiple motion capture spaces.

694
00:28:48,340 --> 00:28:49,640
And I'm gonna pause it here,

695
00:28:49,640 --> 00:28:53,541
and you can see we've got our main actors in the boat here.

696
00:28:54,464 --> 00:28:56,345
And you've got me in the corner,

697
00:28:56,345 --> 00:28:58,486
and what the heck am I doing with this little thing here?

698
00:28:58,486 --> 00:29:00,886
It's kind of hard to see, but you can see a monitor

699
00:29:00,886 --> 00:29:02,867
of what Dory's seeing through his virtual camera,

700
00:29:02,867 --> 00:29:04,228
and here's Kratos and Atreus,

701
00:29:04,228 --> 00:29:06,248
and we've got this giant snake.

702
00:29:06,248 --> 00:29:08,209
Now, obviously, we couldn't build a giant snake.

703
00:29:08,209 --> 00:29:09,970
It wouldn't fit in the mo-cap space.

704
00:29:09,970 --> 00:29:13,031
So what we used was a tiny little box with markers on it,

705
00:29:13,031 --> 00:29:15,712
and I was acting as sort of a puppeteer of the snake.

706
00:29:15,712 --> 00:29:18,353
And then we would take that data and offset it in real time

707
00:29:18,353 --> 00:29:19,853
so that, from Dory's point of view,

708
00:29:19,853 --> 00:29:21,574
he could see the snake in the right place.

709
00:29:22,374 --> 00:29:26,616
and then this little green spot being held by Bruno,

710
00:29:26,616 --> 00:29:29,838
our animation director, was being held up

711
00:29:29,838 --> 00:29:33,799
so that the actors would know where to look

712
00:29:33,799 --> 00:29:34,960
to represent where the snake would be.

713
00:29:34,960 --> 00:29:36,841
Whew, a little complex, but we made it work.

714
00:29:36,841 --> 00:29:39,682
All right, here we've got some onset footage

715
00:29:39,682 --> 00:29:40,723
from the flying boat jump.

716
00:29:40,723 --> 00:29:42,744
Since this was a pretty physical scene,

717
00:29:42,744 --> 00:29:45,925
we ended up using stunt actors.

718
00:29:46,919 --> 00:29:51,242
Here we have one of our stunt actors acting as Kratos,

719
00:29:51,242 --> 00:29:54,084
and he would also double as the ghost Kratos.

720
00:29:54,084 --> 00:29:56,786
And you might see Dory over there kind of offset.

721
00:29:56,786 --> 00:29:59,047
We wanted to keep him out of the way of the stunt actor

722
00:29:59,047 --> 00:30:01,809
so he would not get punched in the face.

723
00:30:01,809 --> 00:30:03,650
And also, it allowed him to get in

724
00:30:03,650 --> 00:30:05,371
and really get that first person camera

725
00:30:05,371 --> 00:30:07,012
without interrupting the actors.

726
00:30:07,012 --> 00:30:08,673
So he's being offset as well.

727
00:30:21,553 --> 00:30:25,874
Like I mentioned when we did our live action previews,

728
00:30:25,874 --> 00:30:28,355
we were gonna break it up into multiple pieces.

729
00:30:28,355 --> 00:30:31,836
So we'll see the second take where we've got our observers.

730
00:30:31,836 --> 00:30:33,776
We've got a stunt stand in for Sonny as Atreus.

731
00:30:33,776 --> 00:30:35,157
Okay, coming in close.

732
00:30:35,157 --> 00:30:37,858
And then we've got Kratos in the back there.

733
00:30:37,858 --> 00:30:39,638
What the hell's that?

734
00:30:39,638 --> 00:30:41,979
And since we had already shot the data for the ghost,

735
00:30:41,979 --> 00:30:44,900
we could see that within the virtual camera.

736
00:30:44,900 --> 00:30:45,960
We gotta go!

737
00:30:45,960 --> 00:30:48,481
Look, there's no time!

738
00:30:48,481 --> 00:30:48,821
Look!

739
00:30:59,235 --> 00:31:00,636
We hadn't animated the barrels yet,

740
00:31:00,636 --> 00:31:01,617
so we just kind of pretended.

741
00:31:01,617 --> 00:31:01,817
And go.

742
00:31:01,817 --> 00:31:02,498
I got a plan.

743
00:31:02,498 --> 00:31:02,918
Jump.

744
00:31:02,918 --> 00:31:05,320
And then here's where we cut,

745
00:31:05,320 --> 00:31:11,126
and we go to the traditional animation for the big fall,

746
00:31:11,126 --> 00:31:14,569
and then we have our final take where they land,

747
00:31:14,569 --> 00:31:16,791
and you know the rest of that scene.

748
00:31:16,791 --> 00:31:18,453
Now what is your plan?

749
00:31:18,453 --> 00:31:19,714
All right.

750
00:31:19,714 --> 00:31:21,456
So after everything is done and shot,

751
00:31:21,456 --> 00:31:23,377
it's time to get all that data back

752
00:31:23,377 --> 00:31:25,159
and assemble it and polish it.

753
00:31:26,069 --> 00:31:28,191
And the first part of that is editing.

754
00:31:28,191 --> 00:31:29,993
I know what you're thinking.

755
00:31:29,993 --> 00:31:30,614
What? Editing?

756
00:31:30,614 --> 00:31:31,835
Why are you editing a one-er?

757
00:31:31,835 --> 00:31:33,276
It's all one shot.

758
00:31:33,276 --> 00:31:36,399
Well, we tried to avoid editing as often as possible

759
00:31:36,399 --> 00:31:38,021
because it's exponentially more difficult

760
00:31:38,021 --> 00:31:39,843
to blend two takes together versus cutting.

761
00:31:40,709 --> 00:31:43,330
But sometimes you have to account for multi-volume scenes

762
00:31:43,330 --> 00:31:45,370
for very large environments.

763
00:31:45,370 --> 00:31:48,011
Sometimes you have to think about unintentional mistakes

764
00:31:48,011 --> 00:31:49,011
that might have happened on set.

765
00:31:49,011 --> 00:31:51,292
Maybe you're getting a really good take,

766
00:31:51,292 --> 00:31:53,472
but then there's just one line that the actor flubs,

767
00:31:53,472 --> 00:31:55,153
so you wanna just do a little insert there

768
00:31:55,153 --> 00:31:56,233
where they get the line right,

769
00:31:56,233 --> 00:31:59,294
and then you'll just merge those two bests together.

770
00:31:59,294 --> 00:32:02,895
Sometimes we need inserts for clarity or script rewrites.

771
00:32:02,895 --> 00:32:04,975
Occasionally we'd have a play test

772
00:32:04,975 --> 00:32:06,496
where the players would give feedback

773
00:32:06,496 --> 00:32:07,996
that they didn't understand what was going on,

774
00:32:07,996 --> 00:32:09,237
so we might do some rewrites.

775
00:32:09,984 --> 00:32:14,947
and shoot something to help clarify that scene.

776
00:32:14,947 --> 00:32:18,670
Also, timing passes in case a scene was running long

777
00:32:18,670 --> 00:32:19,811
or needed some extra time,

778
00:32:19,811 --> 00:32:20,892
we would insert or cut things down.

779
00:32:20,892 --> 00:32:21,132
Cut, yeah.

780
00:32:21,132 --> 00:32:24,935
Also, any changes to level design or environment art,

781
00:32:24,935 --> 00:32:27,577
like you saw in the mocap previz,

782
00:32:27,577 --> 00:32:29,638
we hadn't figured out the entrances or exits,

783
00:32:29,638 --> 00:32:30,959
so sometimes once we nailed that down,

784
00:32:30,959 --> 00:32:33,081
we would do a quick reshoot and get those entrances

785
00:32:33,081 --> 00:32:34,401
nailed down and blend that all together.

