00:36:37,774 --> 00:36:40,215
And of course our flying boat jump.

883
00:36:48,322 --> 00:36:50,543
Some quick numbers about our animation team.

884
00:36:50,543 --> 00:36:53,045
We had an internal team size of about seven animators

885
00:36:53,045 --> 00:36:54,627
at peak production.

886
00:36:54,627 --> 00:36:56,248
We had three different outsource teams,

887
00:36:56,248 --> 00:36:58,310
two vendors helping clean up our body

888
00:36:58,310 --> 00:37:00,592
and one vendor for facial solving.

889
00:37:00,592 --> 00:37:02,733
But our internal animators would have ownership

890
00:37:02,733 --> 00:37:04,895
of all the scenes, including our outsource ones,

891
00:37:04,895 --> 00:37:06,957
so that they could assemble the outsource data

892
00:37:06,957 --> 00:37:08,458
and make sure everything got integrated

893
00:37:08,458 --> 00:37:10,400
and keeping track of the debugging process.

894
00:37:12,209 --> 00:37:15,111
In hindsight, we wished we'd had a larger internal team

895
00:37:15,111 --> 00:37:16,932
because as our contractors rolled off,

896
00:37:16,932 --> 00:37:18,953
we would have to transfer ownership of all those scenes

897
00:37:18,953 --> 00:37:20,834
to all our remaining team members,

898
00:37:20,834 --> 00:37:22,775
and we had over 100 cut scenes to keep track of,

899
00:37:22,775 --> 00:37:23,436
so that was a lot.

900
00:37:23,436 --> 00:37:27,378
Also, just tracking the sheer amount of content

901
00:37:27,378 --> 00:37:29,919
and scope creep, we had a lot of level design asks

902
00:37:29,919 --> 00:37:31,540
that weren't originally in the script,

903
00:37:31,540 --> 00:37:33,361
but we would need to help tell the story

904
00:37:33,361 --> 00:37:35,222
of level design as well.

905
00:37:35,222 --> 00:37:37,144
So now we take into consideration

906
00:37:37,144 --> 00:37:39,585
all of our narrative moments, and not just cinematics,

907
00:37:39,585 --> 00:37:41,266
as we work out our scope and our schedule.

908
00:37:43,155 --> 00:37:47,163
Onto our polish, we had what we called the buttery smooth patch.

909
00:37:47,163 --> 00:37:50,911
What this was was just really troubleshooting those seamless transitions between gameplay

910
00:37:50,911 --> 00:37:53,818
and cinematics to make sure our no-cut language was working.

911
00:37:54,843 --> 00:37:57,164
The main things we were looking for was pose matching,

912
00:37:57,164 --> 00:37:58,564
and that seems pretty obvious,

913
00:37:58,564 --> 00:38:01,305
but it's important to establish those standard poses,

914
00:38:01,305 --> 00:38:02,866
and any time it's changed,

915
00:38:02,866 --> 00:38:05,507
make sure you communicate them widely across the team.

916
00:38:05,507 --> 00:38:07,768
Make sure your pose library is updated,

917
00:38:07,768 --> 00:38:09,788
and see if you can find some tools

918
00:38:09,788 --> 00:38:11,849
that helps the animators match poses and animations

919
00:38:11,849 --> 00:38:13,430
across your scenes and characters.

920
00:38:15,248 --> 00:38:17,589
matching the velocity of the gameplay animation

921
00:38:17,589 --> 00:38:19,010
into a cinematic and back out.

922
00:38:19,010 --> 00:38:21,371
Each of our characters had a zero joint

923
00:38:21,371 --> 00:38:23,792
that indicated their position in the game.

924
00:38:23,792 --> 00:38:25,613
And in the case of Kratos, the player,

925
00:38:25,613 --> 00:38:28,254
the camera is also attached to that zero joint.

926
00:38:28,254 --> 00:38:29,935
So any kind of errant motion was gonna cause

927
00:38:29,935 --> 00:38:31,696
some weird jarring camera blends.

928
00:38:32,407 --> 00:38:34,590
The zero joint's velocity also informs the engine

929
00:38:34,590 --> 00:38:36,492
of what state the character should be in,

930
00:38:36,492 --> 00:38:38,876
whether he's walking or running or idle.

931
00:38:38,876 --> 00:38:40,818
So if it's not matching the actual action of the scene,

932
00:38:40,818 --> 00:38:43,802
if you've animated your cinematic so Kratos is running out,

933
00:38:43,802 --> 00:38:45,325
but your zero joint is frozen,

934
00:38:45,325 --> 00:38:46,787
then the game engine thinks he's standing,

935
00:38:46,787 --> 00:38:48,689
so then you're gonna see him pop into an idle pose

936
00:38:48,689 --> 00:38:49,410
at the end of the scene.

937
00:38:51,475 --> 00:38:53,276
Finally, thinking about metrics.

938
00:38:53,276 --> 00:38:56,438
For any interactable objects such as doors or levers,

939
00:38:56,438 --> 00:38:59,060
we need to get those exact metrics set by the gameplay team

940
00:38:59,060 --> 00:39:01,221
for how close the player should be to that object

941
00:39:01,221 --> 00:39:02,983
at the start of a cinematic.

942
00:39:02,983 --> 00:39:06,065
Here are some issues with buttery smoothness.

